1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,675
A low score does not always mean the AI Agent is weak.

2
00:00:03,625 --> 00:00:09,500
The task may be ambiguous, the environment may be broken, or the grader may reject a valid answer.

3
00:00:09,500 --> 00:00:12,384
Evaluation quality must be tested too.

4
00:00:12,384 --> 00:00:14,884
Start with failures you already see.

5
00:00:14,884 --> 00:00:25,365
Manual checks, support tickets, production bugs, and difficult edge cases are high-value seeds because they represent real user expectations rather than imaginary benchmark puzzles.

6
00:00:25,365 --> 00:00:29,682
Write each task so two qualified reviewers can reach the same verdict.

7
00:00:29,682 --> 00:00:35,653
Include the input, required outcome, important constraints, and everything the grader will inspect.

8
00:00:35,653 --> 00:00:41,865
Then create a reference solution that proves the task is solvable and that the graders can recognize a known good result.

9
00:00:41,865 --> 00:00:44,471
Build balanced sets and begin small.

10
00:00:44,471 --> 00:00:50,394
A useful early suite can contain a few dozen realistic tasks instead of hundreds of weak examples.

11
00:00:50,394 --> 00:00:57,932
As the product matures, add harder cases that distinguish improvements and convert solved capability tests into regression protection.

12
00:00:57,932 --> 00:01:01,076
Read transcripts and grades from many trials.

13
00:01:01,076 --> 00:01:09,009
A failed trace tells you whether the Agent made a genuine mistake, whether the harness blocked progress, or whether the grader punished a reasonable solution.

14
00:01:09,009 --> 00:01:14,019
If failures do not look fair, revise the evaluation before optimizing the Agent.

15
00:01:14,019 --> 00:01:16,528
Treat the suite as a living artifact.

16
00:01:16,528 --> 00:01:22,557
Models improve, products change, user behavior shifts, and once-difficult tasks saturate.

17
00:01:22,557 --> 00:01:29,644
Ownership, regular maintenance, production monitoring, and periodic human calibration keep the signal useful over time.

18
00:01:29,644 --> 00:01:34,576
First, turn real failures into unambiguous tasks with reference solutions.

19
00:01:34,576 --> 00:01:38,875
Second, read transcripts to tell Agent errors from grader errors.

20
00:01:38,875 --> 00:01:43,884
Third, keep the suite current as capabilities, products, and risks change.
